observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the:
a) Inventory Committee to submit the complete RPCPPE, including CIP accounts, not later than January 31 of each year;
b) GSO to (i) maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map, in coordination with the MEO; and (ii) keep Local Road Network Property Card;
c) Concerned Offices to secure documents to establish the transfer/donation to the Municipality of the donated properties; and
d) Municipal Accountant to
(i) maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network;
(ii) henceforth, disclose in the Notes to FS the total road system; and
(iii) recognize the donated properties in the books of accounts.

We recommended and Management agreed for the:

Municipal Accountant to exhaust all remedies to gather the supporting documents for the receivables noted. Henceforth, consider the write-off of dormant accounts for more than 10 years, in accordance with the procedures set forth by COA Circular No. 2016-005;

 Accounting Office and Human Resource Office to require Dr. Frias to immediately liquidate his cash advances either by presenting liquidation documents or by refunding the unsettled cash advances.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:
Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO) and the Municipal Budget Office (MBO) to assist the Municipal Development Council in the i) adherence to the guidelines set by COA Memorandum Circular No. 95-216 in the preparation of the AIP and Annual Budget; and  ii) improvement of project identification particularly those to be charged against the development fund by ensuring that they had undergone priority ranking in terms of developmental impact and necessity;
BAC Secretariat/Concerned Officials to submit copies of contracts entered into by the Municipality and/or issued purchase orders within five days from execution thereof in consonance with COA Circular No. 2009-01.
BAC, BAC Secretariat and Accounting Office to i) submit the lacking documents indicated in paragraphs 6.18 and 6.21 above and explanations for the other issues noted; and ii) adhere with the GPPB Circular 2020-01 concerning the emergency procurement of goods and the revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 for the conduct of public bidding;
Municipal Accountant to check and ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payment; and
Municipal Engineering Office to monitor strictly the implementation of infrastructure projects in order to protect the interests of the government by monitoring contractor compliance with rules and regulations on construction safety.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer’s Office enhance their processes by following the prescribed procedures on reporting and remittance of collections, specifically, we recommended that -
the Municipal Treasurer
decide who between the designated LO and Cashier will be the Municipality’s LO and perform the matching responsibilities;
issue new Office Orders to the designated LO and Cashier for their new responsibilities; and
verify the reports of the LO and acknowledge receipt of cash on the RCD.
the LO should henceforth –
be the one verifying the reports and collating the collections of collectors;
acknowledge receipt of reports and remittances of the ONC on the concerned collectors’ RCDs;
prepare his/her own RCD to report her received remittances from the collectors and the amount remitted to the Municipal Treasurer.
the collectors place reference number in their RCDs and indicate the same reference number in their individual cashbook.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:
MDRRMO to prepare the LDRRMIP in accordance with COA Circular 2012-02;
BAC, BAC Secretariat and Accounting Office to i) submit the lacking documents indicated in paragraphs 14.21 and 14.31 above and explanations for the other issues noted; and ii) adhere to the GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 concerning emergency procurement of goods and the revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 on the conduct of public bidding;
End users to complete the description of items with clarity in the PR to ease evaluation of disbursements;
GSO and EA to submit the required list of recipients with important details such as the actual quantity received, signature of the recipients, date received and the location of recipients for the COVID-19 related procurement for the proper evaluation thereof; and
Municipal Accountant to check and ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payment.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:
Tourism, Accounting, and Treasury Offices to strictly comply with the mandate of the ordinance to remit all proceeds from tourism operation in the trust fund and not to split them with the general fund;
Treasury Office to open a separate bank account exclusively for the STF in accordance with the provision of the ordinance;
Tourism Office, BAC and BAC Secretariat to i) indicate printed names of suppliers’ representatives in the requests for quotations and purchase orders; ii) specify details of needed items in the purchase requests; and iii) observe procurement laws including the preparation of APP when disbursing monies coming from the STF;
Accounting Office to disclose in the Notes to the Financial Statements the income and expenses earned and expended using the STF; and
LDC to i) study the possibility of considering the tourism program as another local economic enterprise (LEE) of the agency especially with the intention of the Municipality to operate the Municipal Eco-Park; ii) prepare necessary feasibility studies to assess the capability of the tourism program to generate steady income especially when facilities have been invested in the area; and iii) treat the STF as special account under the General Fund.
We further recommended that the Tourism and Treasury Offices explain why the rate of trip dues being collected was only ₱300.00 and/or submit copy of any amendment of the said rate.

We recommended that the Management :
comply with the provisions of the revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, specifically the i) posting of ITB, NOA and NTP in the Municipality’s website; ii) invitation of observers during detailed bid evaluation and post qualification; and iii) indicating clear specifications of the items to be procured in the bidding documents;
through the MSWDO, submit attendance sheets during the orientation of the project participants/beneficiaries;
submit to the Audit Team the detailed Project/Training Design and any other documents which are significant for the proper evaluation of the project; and
moving forward, consider adding stipulation on the responsibilities of project beneficiaries to define accountability and ensure sustainability of the program.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:
End-users, BAC and BAC Secretariat to i) specify details of needed items in the PR; and ii) indicate printed names of suppliers’ representatives in the RFQs and POs;
Concerned office in the distribution of facemasks and face shields to submit distribution lists or report on the distribution;
RHU, MHRMO and Budget Office to submit i) DTRs of the PHWs who received SRA during the paid period; ii) authority of PHWs to attend work during the quarantine; iii) proof that the SB had determined the rate of SRA; iv) proof that the Municipality complied with the PS limitation; v) DOH certification that its nurses assigned to the command center of Municipality had not received SRA from its fund; and vi) computations showing that the received SRA by the PHWs is not in excess of what is allowed as one-time SRA under the purview of B.C. No. 2020-2 considering also the payment of both Magna Carta hazard pay and COVID-19 hazard pay; and
Accounting Office to review bases for the grants of allowances/benefits and its recognition of the same in the book of accounts.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

conduct a complete annual physical count of PPEs and come up with RPCPPE with its related reconciliation as required by Section 124 of LGU-NGAS; 


maintain the Property Ledger Cards (PLC) and Property Cards (PC), respectively, for all LGU properties. Also, observe the periodic reconciliation of the two records for proper monitoring of agency assets;

facilitate the preparation of IIRUP and dispose the unserviceable properties pursuant to Section 79 of PD 1445 to prevent further deterioration of these PPEs; and  

gather the necessary details on the value of the five (5) donated motor vehicles and accordingly make the necessary adjustment/recognition in the Agency’s books.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

direct all Accountable Officers to immediately liquidate their cash advances;


establish a thorough monitoring of cash advances granted to different Accountable Officers by making a schedule when these CAs are due for liquidation and issue demand letters if needed; 

 the Accounting Office strictly comply with COA Circular No. 97-002 on the prohibition of granting additional cash advance unless the previous grant is already liquidated by the Accountable Officers; and 

ensure that all cash advance grants are properly supported with documentary requirements such as travel order so as to establish the regularity and validity of these cash advances.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the:

Municipal Engineering Office to complete the remaining projects in the AIP/Annual Budget for CY 2019;

 Municipal Accountant to check and ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payment;

 Bids and Awards Committee to invite qualified observers in every procurement process;

 BAC Secretariat/Concerned Officials to submit the approved contracts and purchase orders within five days from execution thereof in consonance with COA Circular 2009-01; and 

 Municipal Engineer or other officials concerned to strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular 2013-004 to inform the public on matters of public concern with the end in view of promoting good governance through transparency and accountability.

We recommended and Management agreed for the:

LDRRM Officer to prepare the necessary LDRRMFIP annually for the Agency’s programs and projects on Disaster Risk Reduction and Management annually;

 Budget Division to demand for the LDRRMFIP before the release of LDRRMF;

 require the Municipal Engineer to prepare and submit the above lacking documents on the desilting project; and

 direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure the completeness of documents before effecting payments.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

monitor the expenditures disbursed for GAD Programs and check if it is still within the allocated amount in the GPB; 

 enhance the Accomplishment Report for GAD by completely filling out the needed qualitative aspect of the activities implemented including data on sex-aggregation pursuant to MCW, as necessary; 

 ensure that attribution is made in accordance with the HGDG tool and PIMME to determine how much of the Agency’s actual disbursements for implementing its major programs can be attributed to GAD; and

  submit the GAD Plan and Utilization/Accomplishment Report to the Audit Team within the reglementary period provided by COA Circular 2014-001.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:

a) require the Local Finance Committee to include in its budget the insurance expenses of all insurable properties Municipality;

b) require the GSO Officer to facilitate the submission of the updated list of inventory of insurable properties so that the necessary insurance coverage can be applied with the GSIS insurance fund;

c) require the Accounting Office to submit Vouchers No. 100-18-12-2488 and 100-18-12-2494 to COA and ensure the completeness of documents attached on every voucher; and

d) require Accounting and GSO Offices to explain the incurrence of double payment of insurance premium for 2005 Mitsubishi Endeavor.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:
require the Local Finance Committee to include in its budget the insurance expenses of all insurable properties Municipality;
require the GSO Officer to facilitate the submission of the updated list of inventory of insurable properties so that the necessary insurance coverage can be applied with the GSIS insurance fund;
require the Accounting Office to submit Vouchers No. 100-18-12-2488 and 100-18-12-2494 to COA and ensure the completeness of documents attached on every voucher; and
require Accounting and GSO Offices to explain the incurrence of double payment of insurance premium for 2005 Mitsubishi Endeavor.

Endeavor to capacitate themselves through attendance to trainings under GFPS for more responsive planning;

Facilitate the establishment of the GAD Database to aid in gender analysis and provide baseline data on the status of women and men in the LGU; and

Assess the extent of compliance through a compliance checklist of the elements of the institutional mechanisms in place and intensify efforts on those areas that should be in place.
